Dear President Xi Jinping

Many people have welcomed your gaining the presidency in China as you're known to embrace reform where needed.

Music gives people a sense of creative satisfaction and community cohesion, probhiting the singing of songs is sure to create unease and unhappiness amongst citizens.

I hope that you will reform the laws about freedom of expression and allow Lolo to be released from prison immediately. A prison sentence for singing is a terribly unjust manifestation of 'law'.

Yours sincerely

Ms S G Farrell (singer and teacher)

To Xi Jinping

Following the intensive wave of resistance in Tibet in 2011 and 2012, the Chinese government authorised increasingly aggressive measures against individual Tibetans and their communities.

We the undersigned call upon you and the Chinese leadership to:

Account for all Tibetans who have been detained and sentenced in relation to protests, including self-immolation
Allow human rights monitors, UN representatives, journalists and diplomats access to Tibet to investigate excessive use of force against protesters
Ensure that the families of all detainees are informed of their whereabouts and that those in custody have immediate access to legal representation

We the undersigned call upon you and the Chinese leadership to:
 •Account for all Tibetans who have been detained and sentenced in relation to protests, including self-immolation
 •Allow human rights monitors, UN representatives, journalists and diplomats access to Tibet to investigate excessive use of force against protesters
 •Ensure that the families of all detainees are informed of their whereabouts and that those in custody have immediate access to legal representation
 •Amend the law regarding peaceful assembly and freedom of expression to put it in line with international human rights standards

Yours sincerely, 
C Acton

Honorable Secretary General, Vi Jinping, 

I wish you a long, happy, healthy and prosperous life and great success as the leader of the great Nation of the People's Republic of China.  I have always admired your country, its history, culture and, beyond all else, the peoples of China. As a Western Buddhist, and committed socialist, I long to visit China and Tibet, and to share my deep love for both peoples in peace, harmony, and solidarity.      I believe that even just one voice can make a difference around the world.

     Although I was born on the Fourth of July on Chicago's Southside, I am not a typical American.      Robert Stephen Moore

I am but a person from The Netherlands, I am 21 and haven't seen half of the world's suffering. I think I will never truly find out or experience such, living here. I do know it is out there and however I cannot connect with the pain like the people present do; I do feel a sadness.

I read stories on the internet behind my PC. I see pictures of oppression and conflict. And then I sometimes remember that this isn't the life everyone lives today.

As I see the pictures and read the stories I can only but wonder: Why? I think I will never know the exact reasons but I feel that they cannot be so great to inflict this upon a culture and its people. Haven't we seen this before? We have books full of history, of many countries where similiar events happened. Have we not seen what these event bring about? All the nations, cultures and people once oppressed are to this day trying to rebuild their lives. We are not, infact equal. But it is undeniable we're all human and have right to freedom

Lao Tzu said:" Do not conquer the world with force, for force only causes resistance.Thorns spring up when an army passes. Years of misery follow a great victory.Do only what needs to be done without using violence."

To Xi Jinping
 
Following the intensive wave of resistance in Tibet in 2011 and 2012, the Chinese government authorised increasingly aggressive measures against individual Tibetans and their communities. 

We the undersigned call upon you and the Chinese leadership to:
 •Account for all Tibetans who have been detained and sentenced in relation to protests, including self-immolation
 •Allow human rights monitors, UN representatives, journalists and diplomats access to Tibet to investigate excessive use of force against protesters
 •Ensure that the families of all detainees are informed of their whereabouts and that those in custody have immediate access to legal representation
 •Amend the law regarding peaceful assembly and freedom of expression to put it in line with international human rights standards
China can buy the world but it can't buy the dignity

China is trying to do what the US failed in Iraq: creating colonies in a place where a nation has governed the place for over thousand years.  Tibet has unique cultural traditions and its own language, scripts, governments and ruling bodies.  In the 21st century, running colonies is a costly business both in terms of human costs and in actual finance.  Eventually all African and South Asian nations got independent.  

Destruction of the nation's system has resulted in civil war in Iraq.  Over a million Iraqi people died since. America failed in creating colonies in Iraq.  Likewise, China failed to win the hearts and minds of the Tibetan people.  The Chinese rule is costly and inhumane.  Arresting, torturing, and killing Tibetan people will not change their minds on their religious views and their cultural traditions just in the same way that Iraqi people will not convert to Christianity.

Let Tibet run their own place.  Grant freedom and liberty.  Let China be a great nation on earth.

Why?

For what?

do the right thing....

Height increasing shoes and height boost shoe inserts are rapidly gaining popularity for very good motives. A lot of individuals are concerned about their height in that they would like to become taller. Although you'll find methods to enhance body height, such as via height boost exercises or bone elongation surgery, none compare towards the convenience of just getting a pair of height rising shoes or inserts. This article will describe the two most typical types of height growing inserts as well because the most typical kind of height improve shoes: the Yoko / Kimi insoles, and elevator footwear. Yoko / Kimi insoles had been designed based on reflexology principles. Acupressure points exist on the soles of our feet, and every of them is connected to a diverse part or functioning of our physique. The Yoko / Kimi shoe pads are created to possess raised tabs at specific places that, with every single step you take, will exert pressure on particular acupressure points to stimulate the production of human development hormone (HGH for short), which can be a hormone which is believed to be responsible for height enhance. The far more you wear them, the far more effective they tend to become. The downside of those products is the fact that although some people have vouched for their effectiveness in increasing height, walking with these inserts for too lengthy can trigger blisters or bleeding on your soles. This ought to be considered before you take into account acquiring a pair of this sort of insoles. Height enhance elevator footwear, which happen to be around for decades, would be the most popular kind of height boost shoes. Although they will not really make your body taller, these shoes will make you seem taller, which serves the purpose for many individuals. If you acquire a pair of elevator footwear, you will discover hidden inserts inside them that may act to raise your heels to produce you look taller. By wearing them, these footwear can add as much as 2.7 inches for your height. I feel the calling .. there must be something very wrong with the system there and the best I could do at the moment was to sign this petition. Hopefully I will be able to travel there to see myself what's wrong and help any way possible. All the best. God bless!

I went to Lahsa in 1996 and I got some negative obinrvatsoes to the local monks. I saw two monks were kicking a begger in front of a group tourists in a monastery, and I saw a  small monk  could only sit beside a living buddha while he was eating and ate the remain of the food after the living buddha finished his dinner.I had an impression that ordinary local Tibetan had no reason to hate the communists as they saved them from slavery.  I felt that Chinese troop has much more reason to stay in Tibet than US troop's entering into and staying in Iraq.  After all, Tibet became part of China from more than 1000 year ago and for the past several hundred years no Dala Lahma could become Dala Lahma without Chinese central government's confirmation, and for the past several hundred years Chinese central governments' army stationed in Tibet.  British colonists tried to occupy Tibet but were defeated by local troops decades ago.That's what many ordinary Chinese's opinions about Tibet.  I believe what you ordinary Westerners learned about Tibet is far from the truth about the history and reality of Tibet. In one word, Tibet was, is and will be in foreseeable future part of China, and the majority of Tibetan has been emancipated from slavery by Chinese communists about 30 years ago.  Those who are most longing for indepedence are monks who could be the governing class if it is not for the sake of the communists, and then they could kick as fiercely as they could any ordinary local people in front of tourists, and enjoy all the good things contributed by ignorant local people.  Hating totalitarian and censorship should not be a reason to ignore some basic facts about Tibet: the protestors are not peaceful, they are killing and setting fire, burning girls and cutting ears from alive persons.  Deliberately turning blind to these photos, even if they were released by Chinese governmental media, and calling those protestors  peaceful  is a shame to CNN, if it knew that there still existed something called  shame .  I hope my above words will not be censored, as you are not communists, right?

To Xi Jinping

Following the intensive wave of resistance in Tibet in 2011 and 2012, the Chinese government authorised increasingly aggressive measures against individual Tibetans and their communities.

We the undersigned call upon you and the Chinese leadership to:

    Account for all Tibetans who have been detained and sentenced in relation to protests, including self-immolation
    Allow human rights monitors, UN representatives, journalists and diplomats access to Tibet to investigate excessive use of force against protesters
    Ensure that the families of all detainees are informed of their whereabouts and that those in custody have immediate access to legal representation
    Amend the law regarding peaceful assembly and freedom of expression to put it in line with international human rights standards

Andreas Späth
